results.notes: These sizable orbs fruit prolifically in the lawns throughout my neighborhood, much to the consternation of homeowners, as Kuo describes on his Mushroom Expert web site. They arise from the soil, appearing as a solid ball at first, then split open and gradually turn back the edges of the rind into 7 or 8 “rays” revealing the spore mass inside. I have found them in various stages, but have never had an opportunity to capture the developmental process in a series of photographs before. I thought I would take a photo every day for a week, thinking this specimen would fruit and decay quickly as fleshy mushrooms do. To my surprise, however, the developmental stages progressed very slowly … over weeks, not days. This collage shows the development over the past four weeks. The additional photo, taken today, shows the specimen buried under a layer of icy snow. My intention is to create a follow-up collage as this specimen progresses to its final stage of decay … if I am able to capture this process between snowfalls.

Hello everybody. Happy Holidays!

I am new at this , and need help to identify these mushrooms please.

I found these mushrooms now in middle of December and also previous years , at the same time and place. They grow on my property in Northern California in the mixed forest under oak and madrone trees ( in leaves). Mushrooms are very clean and have no bad odor. And they do not stain any color when cut or bruised. Tops are firm and sort of thick and almost look edible. They are also not perfectly round. The tops are not slimy or sticky. They are sort of dry and have velvet feel to them. Tops are light reddish brown color, sort of like dark tan. There are no skirts , scales or other strange looking grows on them. Very clean White color gills and steam. Gilss are tight together and close to the stem. Steam is not very dense, but also not very soft either. Spore print is white on black and also on white paper. They measure aprox. Big mushroom is 4" high, top 4 1/2" diameter.

I think this is all I can tell. Please help me to identify these great looking mushrooms. Thank you in advance.

results.notes:
Location is upper Morro Creek along Highway 41 West, between Morro Bay and Atascadero.
Habitat is riparian, with a dense canopy of live oak, California bay, sycamore and willow. The specific location is a deep shaded canyon.
Substrate is non-calcareous rock situated at or just above the high flood line of the creek. Probably does not become inundated.

Thallus thin, continuous-areolate, greenish, K- Apothecia seeming to start immersed and become sessile, often with thallus material clinging to the margin or margin appearing to be lacking entirely (becoming carbonized?), lecanorine with dark brown-black disk and lighter margin, when visible. Hymenium and hypothecium hyaline, epihymenium light orange-brown, K-.

Spores 8/ascus, hyaline becoming grey to brown, 1-septate, ellipsoid, swollen at septum. Ave. 22.1 × 11.4µm (n=9). I’m no good at determining spore type, but these look similar to the Mischoblastia-type.

Seems to be something close to Rinodina oxydata, but that should by K+Y. Rinodina pacifica has Physconia type spores that are the right size for this collection.

Comment: Distinctly pink spore mass of mature aethalia and flexible pseudocapillitium threads distinguish this find from Lycogala epidendrum (L.) Fries (gray spore mass and fragile threads) and determine it as Lycogala terrestre Fries. (Ref.: 1 and 5). However, not all authors recognize both taxa. Some consider Lycogala terrestre as variety of Lycogala epidendrum, some synonimyze them (Ref.4). What surprises with this find is unusual surface of spores. Almost all sources state minutely reticulated spores for both Lycogala epidendrum and Lycogala terrestre, while the spores observed show quite coarse reticulation. Also aethalia show both, almost smooth, minutely spinulose, as well as coarsely, transversally wrinkled surface of pseudocapillitium threads.

About 12-13 aethalia found. Average diameter 6.7 mm, SD = 1.7 mm (min = 3.5 mm, max = 9.2 mm). Peridium thin but strong, flexible. Pseudocapillitium threads flexible.
